    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_97340078" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/97340078" />
    <a title="Susan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/878571-susan"><img alt="Susan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1231989634p2/878571.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/97340078?book_show_action=true">Apr 06, 2010</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Susan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Susan" href="/user/show/878571-susan">Susan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/878571-susan?shelf=read_and_review">read_and_review</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer97340078" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5998630150966554359">Minoui&apos;s introduction is entirely too precious, beginning &quot;Once upon a time there was a magical land...&quot; She calls Yemen &quot;a mysterious place,&quot; says &quot;women hide their charms behind thick black veils,&quot; and describes Nujood as &quot;a tiny wisp of a thing.&quot; It&apos;s all very poetic, but she&apos;s a journalist writing a serious book, even if it is for children. By the way, &quot;Yemen has experienced a series of civil wars too complicated for the pages of children&apos;s books.&quot; Well, that might explain her apparent belie</span>
  <span id="freeText5998630150966554359" style="display:none">Minoui's introduction is entirely too precious, beginning "Once upon a time there was a magical land..." She calls Yemen "a mysterious place," says "women hide their charms behind thick black veils," and describes Nujood as "a tiny wisp of a thing." It's all very poetic, but she's a journalist writing a serious book, even if it is for children. By the way, "Yemen has experienced a series of civil wars too complicated for the pages of children's books." Well, that might explain her apparent belief things have to be given a Disney spin.<br /><br />Luckily she restrains herself somewhat in the main part of the book, which is told from Nujood's point of view. I'm sure Delphine is letting her own point of view seep through, especially in lines like "[my mother:] had wed through an arranged marriage, like most Yemeni women, so she was in a good position to know that in our country it's the men who give the orders, and the women who follow them. For her to defend me was a waste of time." However, for the most part, she appears to tell Nujood's story as it was told to her. The bare facts--she married off by her family before the legal age of consent, and was the first girl to obtain a divorce--make the story an important one. In addition to her own troubles, Nujood finally learns some family secrets about her older sisters and the difficulties they had, which had been covered up by family members trying to preserve honor.<br /><br />I would be very interested to read something written by Nujood after she grows up, has some perspective on these events, and is able to communicate for herself. But for now, this gets her story heard.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5998630150966554359" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


